{{short description|Ancient Greek goddess of revolt, just retribution, and balance between good and evil}} {{Unreferenced|date=May 2012}}{{Other uses|Adrasteia (Greek mythology)}} {{Infobox deity | type = Greek | name = Adrestia | image = File:F2217a867a074d750b6b79332b8f7f31.jpg.jpg | alt = | caption = Adrestia | god_of = Goddess of equilibrium, balance between good and evil, just retribution and revolt; handmaiden of Nemesis | abode = [[Mount Olympus]] | symbol = | consort = | parents = [[Aphrodite]] and [[Ares]] | siblings = [[Eros]], [[Anteros]], [[Phobos (mythology)|Phobos]], [[Deimos (mythology)|Deimos]], and [[Harmonia (mythology)|Harmonia]] | children = | mount = | Roman_equivalent = }}
'''Adrestia''' ([[Ancient Greek]]: Ἀδρήστεια) in [[Greek mythology]] "she who cannot be escaped" is the daughter of [[Ares]] and [[Aphrodite]] and known to accompany her father Ares to war. She was venerated as a goddess of revolt, just retribution and sublime balance between good and evil. Because of her role in revenge and retribution, she was usually portrayed with [[Nemesis (mythology)|Nemesis]], and sometimes identical to Nemesis herself, who had the epithet of [[Adrasteia|Adrestia or Adrasteia]]. She was also believed to be another war figure, similar to her brothers [[Phobos (mythology)|Phobos]] and [[Deimos (mythology)|Deimos]].
{{quote|"She whom none can escape". Properly an epithet of [[Rhea (mythology)|Rhea]] [[Cybele]] in her attribute of the Mother who punishes human injustice, which is a transgression of the natural right order of things. The Greeks and Romans identified her with Nemesis.|Micha F. Lindemans}}
The union between Ares and Aphrodite produced many children: [[Eros]] (the god of love), [[Anteros]] (the god of requited love), Phobos (the god of fear), Deimos (the god of terror) and [[Harmonia (mythology)|Harmonia]] (the goddess of harmony and concord), besides Adrestia herself. Gods would try to get on her side and she would be fought over by the gods and titans.
