{{Infobox language family |name=Finisterre |region=[[New Guinea]] |familycolor=Papuan |fam1=[[Trans–New Guinea languages|Trans–New Guinea]] |fam2=Morobe – Eastern Highlands |fam3=[[Finisterre–Huon languages|Finisterre–Huon]] |child1=Erap |child2=Gusap–Mot |child3=Uruwa |child4=Wantoat |child5=Warup |child6=Yupna |glotto=fini1245 |glottorefname=Finisterre–Saruwaged }}
The '''Finisterre languages''' are a [[language family|family]] within the original [[Trans–New Guinea languages|Trans&ndash;New Guinea]] (TNG) proposal, and [[William A. Foley]] considers their TNG identity to be established. They share with the [[Huon languages]] verbs that are [[suppletion|suppletive]] depending on the person and number of the object, strong morphological evidence that they are related.
==Internal structure== Huon and Finisterre, and then the connection between them, were identified by [[Kenneth McElhanon]] (1967, 1970). They are clearly valid language families. Finisterre contains six clear branches. Beyond that, classification is based on lexicostatistics, which is generally unreliable. The outline below follows McElhanon and Carter et al. (2012).
* '''Finisterre''' family ** Erap branch ***Boana: [[Nuk language|Nuk]]–[[Nek language|Nek]], [[Nakama language|Nakama]], [[Numanggang language|Numanggang]], [[Munkip language|Munkip]] ***[[Finongan language|Finongan]], [[Gusan language|Gusan]], [[Mamaa language|Mamaa]] ***[[Nimi language|Nimi]], [[Ma Manda language|Sauk]] (Ma Manda), [[Uri language|Uri]] ** Gusap–Mot branch ***[[Madi language (Papuan)|Madi]] (Gira), [[Neko language|Neko]], [[Nekgini language|Nekgini]] ***[[Ngaing language|Ngaing]], [[Rawa language|Rawa]], [[Ufim language|Ufim]], [[Iyo language|Iyo]] (Nahu) ** Uruwa branch: [[Sakam language|Sakam]] (Kutong) – [[Som language|Som]], [[Nukna language|Nukna]] (Komutu), [[Yau language|Yau]], ?[[Weliki language|Weliki]] ** Wantoat branch: [[Awara language|Awara]]–[[Wantoat language|Wantoat]] (Yagawak, Bam), [[Tuma-Irumu language|Tuma-Irumu]] ** Warup branch: [[Asaro'o language|Asaro'o]] (Morafa) – Molet, [[Bulgebi language|Bulgebi]], [[Degenan language|Degenan]], [[Forak language|Forak]], [[Guya language|Guya]] (Guiarak), [[Gwahatike language|Gwahatike]] (Dahating), [[Muratayak language|Muratayak]] (Asat, Yagomi) ** Yupna branch: [[Domung language|Domung]]–[[Ma language (Papuan)|Ma]] (Mebu), [[Nankina language|Nankina]], [[Bonkiman language|Bonkiman]]–[[Yopno language|Yopno]] (Kewieng, Wandabong, Nokopo, Isan), ?[[Yout Wam language|Yout Wam]]
